metadata.name: SC.002 : Studies Series #57
metadata.description:
This hybrid project combines elements of 2 previous drops: Glomularus + Inertial Packing. The project is intended as a giveaway to show appreciation to the community of collectors who previously have minted my work.

SC.002 includes multiple constraint systems, based on Verlet and Euler Integration approaches, with attached geometric primitives and softbody Prototubes. Numerous user controls are included:

Interaction:

Mouse/Trackpad:
drag -> camera rotation
drag + CMD/CTR -> camera pan
scroll wheel/pinch -> camera zoom

Key Input:
-, +: reduce | increase Node Count
{, }: reduce | increase Packing Dimension
c, v: reduce | increase Node Adhesion
h, j: reduce | increase Node Jitter
b, n: disable| enable Node-Node Collision
z, x: reduce | increase Stick Constraint
a, s: hide | show Nodes
q, w: hide | show Wireframe
d, f: reduce | increase Prototube Thickness
p: screen capture

Tip:
1. There are 8 unique geometries, should you be inclined to collect a full set.
2. Bringing values outside of "rational" range is encouraged.

Note:
Please post your favorite SC.002 screen captures
TW: @iragreenberg
IG: @greenberg.ira

Built with Three.js, PByte.js, TypeScript, Node

metadata.name: RGB Elementary Cellular Automaton #431
metadata.description:
Stephen Wolfram's Elementary Cellular Automaton where 3 different rules are drawn in the Red, Green and Blue color components of the image.

Rules are selected randomly among a pre-selection of 53 rules from which nice behaviors emerge.

Tokens can have a cell size in the [1; 20] range.

metadata.name: reborn #154
metadata.description:
This is an album of cities too ideal to ever materialise.

It consists of 256 algorithmically generated plans that resemble drawings of Vincenzo Scamozzi, Pietro Cataneo, Filarete and other theorists of the Italian Renaissance. The cities differ in size, the grid of the streets, the landscape around them and the people that inhabit their utopian walls. They carry names that are Italian exonyms of real European cities, drawing a vision of a different world that enacts a mixture of military perfection with social superiority. Flawless, harmonious, unconquerable and utterly impossible.

History brought us many theories about ideal cities, but very few examples exist today. Italian Palmanova or Polish ZamoÅ›Ä‡ are the few to remind us how hard it is to shape reality according to ideals. When confronted with the material world, its idealism becomes the city's grates foe.

To zoom, press a mouse button over the image or touch the screen. To pan, keep the mouse pressed and move it around.

metadata.name: Ethereal Microcosm #243
metadata.description:
An exploration of algorithmic organisms in a contained environment.

This piece is about the simulation of microscopic patterns using a high number of even tinier agents all following the same rules. Different species evolve and interact together, resulting in stabilizing patterns out of their parametric configurations. A form of artificial life.

This work is based on the paper "Characteristics of pattern formation and evolution in approximations of physarum transport networks", written by Jeff Jones and popularized in the artistic field by Sage Jenson. Some features were added to increase the visual and behavioral complexity of the system. Agents are divided into different species, with their own set of rules and interacting with their own substrate. Substrates also interact with each other and agents will mutate in contact of some of them.

metadata.name: Orchard #334
metadata.description:
A natural media rendering of a fruit tree during one of the four seasons. Sometimes, you'll catch it at night - with lights strung on the tree!

The amount of color in spring and fall, snow in winter, fruit on and off the tree will all vary. There are four spring bloom palettes, four trunk colors, and seven types of fruit.
